  "notes": "Fire Pro Wrestling World on SNES (1994) communicates game state primarily through sprite animation, wrestler physique/attire variety, and ring environment transformation. The game lacks narrative faction systems but uses visual wrestler archetype differentiation to represent distinct wrestling styles (lucha-libre masked vs. strong-style heavyweight). Danger is conveyed through exhaustion animation, submission/knockdown states, and match-type environmental hazards. The timing-based grappling system means that visual feedback of opponent positioning and state becomes critical to player decision-making. Edit mode's influence is not directly relevant to passive state communication but indicates the game's commitment to granular visual customization for faction/identity expression.",
